{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:51:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:51:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.13,0.06,0.28,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50633"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5188"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21662"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman with bipolar affective disorder is started on lithium treatment. Her psychiatrist explains that lithium works by affecting certain chemical processes in brain cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main mechanism by which lithium works in the brain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of inositol monophosphatase","Blocking of glutamate receptors","Inhibition of serotonin reuptake","Enhancement of gamma-aminobutyric acid transmission","Antagonism of dopamine receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELithium primarily works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting inositol monophosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E, an enzyme involved in brain cell signalling. This affects how brain cells communicate and adapt to signals by disrupting the phosphatidylinositol cycle and reducing inositol recycling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for medications like ketamine and some antiepileptic drugs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of serotonin reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E is how selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors work in treating depression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancement of gamma-aminobutyric acid transmission\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism for medications like benzodiazepines\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonism of dopamine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is how antipsychotic medications work\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELithium\u0027s unique mechanism of action through inositol monophosphatase inhibition distinguishes it from other psychiatric medications that primarily target neurotransmitter systems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lithium\u0027s primary therapeutic mechanism in bipolar disorder is inhibition of inositol monophosphatase, which disrupts cell signalling pathways.","Lithium reduces inositol recycling by blocking the phosphatidylinositol cycle.","Lithium\u0027s mechanism is distinct from other psychiatric medications that target neurotransmitter systems."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:24:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:26:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7433"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65196"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":nul